import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Log.Base

import QuantumInfo.Finite.Entropy
import QuantumInfo.Finite.CPTPMap
import QuantumInfo.Finite.Distance


/-! # Quantum Capacity

This focuses on defining and proving theorems about the quantum capacity, the maximum asymptotic rate at which quantum information can be coherently transmitted. The precise definition is not consistent in the literature, see [Capacity_doc](./QuantumInfo/Finite/Capacity_doc.html) for a note on what has been used and how that was used to arrive at the following definition:

 1. A channel A `Emulates` another channel B if there are D and E such that D‚ąėA‚ąėE = B.
 2. A channel A `őĶApproximates` channel B (of the same dimensions) if the for every state ŌĀ, the fidelity F(A(ŌĀ), B(ŌĀ)) is at least 1-őĶ.
 3. A channel A `AchievesRate` R:‚ĄĚ if for every őĶ>0, n copies of A emulates some channel B such that log2(dimout(B))/n ‚Č• R, and that B is őĶApproximately the identity.
 4. The `quantumCapacity` of the channel A is the supremum of the achievable rates, i.e. `sSup { R : ‚ĄĚ | AchievesRate A R }`.

The most basic facts:
 * `emulates_self`: Every channel emulates itself.
 * `emulates_trans`: If A emulates B and B emulates C, then A emulates C. (That is, emulation is an ordering.)
 * `őĶApproximates A B őĶ` is equivalent to the existence of some őī (depending őĶ and dims(A)) so that |A-B| has diamond norm at most őī, and őī‚Üí0 as őĶ‚Üí0.
 * `achievesRate_0`: Every channel achievesRate 0. So, the set of achievable rates is Nonempty.
 * If a channel achievesRate R‚āĀ, it also every achievesRate R‚āā every R‚āā ‚Č§ R‚āĀ, i.e. it is an interval extending left towards -‚ąě. Achievable rates are `¬¨BddBelow`.
 * `bddAbove_achievesRate`: A channel C : dimX ‚Üí dimY cannot achievesRate R with `R > log2(min(dimX, dimY))`. Thus, the interval is `BddAbove`.

The nice lemmas we would want:
 * Capacity of a replacement channel is zero.
 * Capacity of an identity channel is `log2(D)`.
 * Capacity is superadditive under tensor products. (That is, at least additive. Showing that it isn't _exactly_ additive, unlike classical capacity which is additive, is a much harder task.)
 * Capacity of a kth tensor power is exactly k times the capacity of the original channel.
 * Capacity does not decrease under tensor sums.
 * Capacity does not increase under composition.

Then, we should show that our definition is equivalent to some above. Most, except (3), should be not too hard to prove.

Then the LSD theorem establishes that the single-copy coherent information is a lower bound. This is stated in `coherentInfo_le_quantumCapacity`. The corollary, that the n-copy coherent information converges to the capacity, is `quantumCapacity_eq_piProd_coherentInfo`.

# TODO

The only notion of "capacity" here currently is "quantum capacity" in the usual sense. But there are several non-equal capacities relevant to quantum channels, see e.g. [Watrous's notes](https://cs.uwaterloo.ca/~watrous/TQI/TQI.8.pdf) for a list:
 * Quantum capacity (`quantumCapacity`)
 * Quantum 1-shot capacity
 * Entanglement-assisted classical capacity
 * Qss, the quantum side-channel capacity
 * Holevo capacity, aka Holevo Ōá. The Holevo‚ÄďSchumacher‚ÄďWestmoreland theorem as a major theorem
 * Entanglement-assisted Holevo capacity
 * Entanglement-assisted quantum capacity
 * One- and two-way distillable entanglement

And other important theorems like superdense coding, nonadditivity, superactivation
-/

namespace CPTPMap

variable {d‚āĀ d‚āā d‚āÉ d‚āĄ d‚āÖ d‚āÜ : Type*}
variable [Fintype d‚āĀ] [Fintype d‚āā] [Fintype d‚āÉ] [Fintype d‚āĄ] [Fintype d‚āÖ] [Fintype d‚āÜ] [DecidableEq d‚āĀ] [DecidableEq d‚āā]

variable [DecidableEq d‚āÉ] [DecidableEq d‚āĄ] in
/--
A channel őõ‚āĀ `Emulates` another channel őõ‚āā if there are D and E such that D‚ąėőõ‚āĀ‚ąėE = őõ‚āā.
-/
def Emulates (őõ‚āĀ : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) (őõ‚āā : CPTPMap d‚āÉ d‚āĄ) : Prop :=
  ‚ąÉ (E : CPTPMap d‚āÉ d‚āĀ) (D : CPTPMap d‚āā d‚āĄ), D.compose (őõ‚āĀ.compose E) = őõ‚āā

/--
A channel A `őĶApproximates` channel B of the same dimensions if the for every state ŌĀ, the fidelity F(A(ŌĀ), B(ŌĀ)) is at least 1-őĶ.
-/
def őĶApproximates (A B : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) (őĶ : ‚ĄĚ) : Prop :=
  ‚ąÄ (ŌĀ : MState d‚āĀ), (A ŌĀ).fidelity (B ŌĀ) ‚Č• 1-őĶ

/--
A channel A `AchievesRate` R:‚ĄĚ if for every őĶ>0, some n copies of A emulates a channel B such that log2(dimout(B))/n ‚Č• R, and that B őĶApproximates the identity channel.
-/
def AchievesRate (A : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) (R : ‚ĄĚ) : Prop :=
  ‚ąÄ őĶ : ‚ĄĚ, őĶ > 0 ‚Üí
    ‚ąÉ n > 0, ‚ąÉ (dimB : ‚Ąē) (B : CPTPMap (Fin dimB) (Fin dimB)),
      (CPTPMap.piProd (fun (_ : Fin n) ‚Ü¶ A)).Emulates B ‚ąß
      Real.logb 2 dimB ‚Č• R*n ‚ąß
      B.őĶApproximates CPTPMap.id őĶ

noncomputable def quantumCapacity (A : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) : ‚ĄĚ :=
  sSup { R : ‚ĄĚ | AchievesRate A R }

section emulates
variable [DecidableEq d‚āÉ] [DecidableEq d‚āĄ] [DecidableEq d‚āÖ]

/-- Every quantum channel emulates itself. -/
@[refl]
theorem emulates_self (őõ : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) : őõ.Emulates őõ :=
  ‚ü®CPTPMap.id, CPTPMap.id, by simp‚ü©

/-- If a quantum channel A emulates B, and B emulates C, then A emulates C. -/
@[trans]
theorem emulates_trans (őõ‚āĀ : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) (őõ‚āā : CPTPMap d‚āÉ d‚āĄ) (őõ‚āÉ : CPTPMap d‚āÖ d‚āÜ)
  (h‚āĀ‚āā : őõ‚āĀ.Emulates őõ‚āā) (h‚āā‚āÉ : őõ‚āā.Emulates őõ‚āÉ) : őõ‚āĀ.Emulates őõ‚āÉ := by
  obtain ‚ü®E‚āĀ, D‚āĀ, hED‚āĀ‚ü© := h‚āĀ‚āā
  obtain ‚ü®E‚āā, D‚āā, hED‚āā‚ü© := h‚āā‚āÉ
  exact ‚ü®E‚āĀ.compose E‚āā, D‚āā.compose D‚āĀ, by classical simp [‚Üź hED‚āĀ, ‚Üź hED‚āā, compose_assoc]‚ü©

end emulates

section őĶApproximates

/-- Every quantum channel perfectly approximates itself, that is, `őĶApproximates` with `őĶ = 0`. -/
theorem őĶApproximates_self (őõ : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) : őõ.őĶApproximates őõ 0 :=
  fun ŌĀ ‚Ü¶ ((őõ ŌĀ).fidelity_self_eq_one.trans (sub_zero 1).symm).ge

/-- If a quantum channel A approximates B with őĶ‚āÄ, it also approximates B with all larger őĶ‚āĀ. -/
theorem őĶApproximates_monotone {A B : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā} {őĶ‚āÄ : ‚ĄĚ} (h : A.őĶApproximates B őĶ‚āÄ)
    {őĶ‚āĀ : ‚ĄĚ} (h‚āā : őĶ‚āÄ ‚Č§ őĶ‚āĀ) : A.őĶApproximates B őĶ‚āĀ :=
  fun ŌĀ ‚Ü¶ (tsub_le_tsub_left h‚āā 1).trans (h ŌĀ)

end őĶApproximates

section AchievesRate

--PULLOUT
instance [Nonempty d‚āĀ] [Nonempty d‚āā] : Nonempty (CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) := by
  sorry

/-- Every quantum channel achieves a rate of zero. -/
theorem achievesRate_0 (őõ : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) : őõ.AchievesRate 0 := by
  intro őĶ hőĶ
  use 1, zero_lt_one, 1, default
  constructor
  ¬∑ have : Nonempty d‚āĀ := by sorry--having a CPTPMap should be enough to conclude in- and out-spaces are nonempty
    have : Nonempty d‚āā := őõ.toPTPMap.nonemptyOut
    use Classical.ofNonempty, Classical.ofNonempty
    exact Unique.eq_default _
  constructor
  ¬∑ norm_num
  ¬∑ rw [Unique.eq_default id]
    exact őĶApproximates_monotone (őĶApproximates_self default) hőĶ.le

/-- The identity channel on D dimensional space achieves a rate of log2(D). -/
theorem id_achievesRate_log_dim : (id (dIn := d‚āĀ)).AchievesRate (Real.logb 2 (Fintype.card d‚āĀ)) := by
  intro őĶ hőĶ
  use 1, zero_lt_one, Fintype.card d‚āĀ, id
  constructor
  ¬∑ --they are equivalent up to permutation
    -- TODO: Instead this proof should be `@[simp] piProd (fun x => id) = id` and `emulates_self`
    refine' ‚ü® _, _, _ ‚ü©;
    exact CPTPMap.ofEquiv ( Fintype.equivFinOfCardEq ( by simp +decide ) ).symm;
    exact CPTPMap.ofEquiv ( Fintype.equivFinOfCardEq ( by simp +decide ) );
    apply CPTPMap.ext;
    ext; simp +decide [ CPTPMap.piProd ];
    unfold MatrixMap.piKron
    simp_all only [gt_iff_lt, PiTensorProduct.map_id, LinearMap.toMatrix_id_eq_basis_toMatrix,
      Module.Basis.toMatrix_self, Matrix.reindex_apply, Matrix.submatrix_one_equiv, Matrix.toLin_one]
    erw [ MatrixMap.submatrix_apply ]
    simp_all only [Equiv.symm_symm, Equiv.apply_symm_apply, Matrix.submatrix_apply]
  constructor
  ¬∑ norm_num
  ¬∑ exact őĶApproximates_monotone (őĶApproximates_self id) hőĶ.le

/-- A channel cannot achieve a rate greater than log2(D), where D is the input dimension. -/
theorem not_achievesRate_gt_log_dim_in (őõ : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) {R : ‚ĄĚ} (hR : Real.logb 2 (Fintype.card d‚āĀ) < R) :
    ¬¨őõ.AchievesRate R := by
  sorry

noncomputable section AristotleLemmas

--PULLOUT
/-
Composition of `piKron` maps distributes over the tensor product.
-/
theorem _root_.MatrixMap.piKron_comp {őĻ : Type*} [Fintype őĻ] [DecidableEq őĻ]
  {R : Type*} [CommSemiring R]
  {d‚āĀ d‚āā d‚āÉ : őĻ ‚Üí Type*}
  [‚ąÄ i, Fintype (d‚āĀ i)] [‚ąÄ i, DecidableEq (d‚āĀ i)]
  [‚ąÄ i, Fintype (d‚āā i)] [‚ąÄ i, DecidableEq (d‚āā i)]
  [‚ąÄ i, Fintype (d‚āÉ i)] [‚ąÄ i, DecidableEq (d‚āÉ i)]
  (őõ‚āĀ : ‚ąÄ i, MatrixMap (d‚āĀ i) (d‚āā i) R) (őõ‚āā : ‚ąÄ i, MatrixMap (d‚āā i) (d‚āÉ i) R) :
    MatrixMap.piKron (fun i => (őõ‚āā i) ‚ąė‚āó (őõ‚āĀ i)) = (MatrixMap.piKron őõ‚āā) ‚ąė‚āó (MatrixMap.piKron őõ‚āĀ) := by
  simp +decide [ MatrixMap.piKron, PiTensorProduct.map_comp, ‚Üź Matrix.toLin_mul ];
  rw [ ‚Üź LinearMap.toMatrix_comp ]

--PULLOUT
/-
The tensor product of composed maps is the composition of the tensor products.
-/
theorem piProd_compose {őĻ : Type*} [Fintype őĻ] [DecidableEq őĻ]
  {d‚āĀ d‚āā d‚āÉ : őĻ ‚Üí Type*}
  [‚ąÄ i, Fintype (d‚āĀ i)] [‚ąÄ i, DecidableEq (d‚āĀ i)]
  [‚ąÄ i, Fintype (d‚āā i)] [‚ąÄ i, DecidableEq (d‚āā i)]
  [‚ąÄ i, Fintype (d‚āÉ i)] [‚ąÄ i, DecidableEq (d‚āÉ i)]
  (őõ‚āĀ : ‚ąÄ i, CPTPMap (d‚āĀ i) (d‚āā i)) (őõ‚āā : ‚ąÄ i, CPTPMap (d‚āā i) (d‚āÉ i)) :
  CPTPMap.piProd (fun i => (őõ‚āā i) ‚ąė‚āė (őõ‚āĀ i)) = (CPTPMap.piProd őõ‚āā) ‚ąė‚āė (CPTPMap.piProd őõ‚āĀ) := by
    refine' ( CPTPMap.ext _ );
    convert MatrixMap.piKron_comp _ _;
    infer_instance

end AristotleLemmas

/-- A channel cannot achieve a rate greater than log2(D), where D is the output dimension. -/
theorem not_achievesRate_gt_log_dim_out (őõ : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) {R : ‚ĄĚ} (hR : Real.logb 2 (Fintype.card d‚āā) < R): ¬¨őõ.AchievesRate R := by
  intro h;
  -- We show that the identity channel on the output space `d‚āā` emulates `őõ`. Since capacity is monotonic under emulation, `Q(őõ) ‚Č§ Q(id_{d‚āā})`.
  have h_emulate : (CPTPMap.id (dIn := d‚āā)).Emulates őõ := by
    exact ‚ü®őõ, CPTPMap.id, by simp‚ü©
  -- If `őõ` achieves rate `R`, then `id_{d‚āā}` achieves rate `R`. This follows because if `őõ^{\otimes n}` emulates `B`, and `id^{\otimes n}` emulates `őõ^{\otimes n}` (by functoriality of tensor product), then `id^{\otimes n}` emulates `B`.
  have h_id_achieves : (CPTPMap.id (dIn := d‚āā)).AchievesRate R := by
    intro őĶ hőĶ_pos
    obtain ‚ü®n, hn, dimB, B, hB_emulate, hB_rate, hB_approx‚ü© := h őĶ hőĶ_pos
    have h_id_emulate : (CPTPMap.piProd (fun (_ : Fin n) => CPTPMap.id (dIn := d‚āā))).Emulates B := by
      -- Since `id_{d‚āā}` emulates `őõ`, we can use the fact that the tensor product of emulations is an emulation.
      have h_tensor_emulate : ‚ąÄ (n : ‚Ąē), (CPTPMap.piProd (fun (_ : Fin n) => CPTPMap.id (dIn := d‚āā))).Emulates (CPTPMap.piProd (fun (_ : Fin n) => őõ)) := by
        intro n
        obtain ‚ü®E, D, hD‚ü© := h_emulate
        use CPTPMap.piProd (fun (_ : Fin n) => E), CPTPMap.piProd (fun (_ : Fin n) => D);
        simp [ ‚Üź hD, ‚Üź CPTPMap.piProd_compose ];
      exact emulates_trans _ _ _ ( h_tensor_emulate n ) hB_emulate;
    exact ‚ü® n, hn, dimB, B, h_id_emulate, hB_rate, hB_approx ‚ü©;
  refine not_le_of_gt hR <| not_lt.mp fun h => ?_
  exact not_lt_of_ge ( le_of_not_gt fun h' => not_achievesRate_gt_log_dim_in _ h' h_id_achieves ) h

/-- The achievable rates are a bounded set. -/
theorem bddAbove_achievesRate (őõ : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) : BddAbove {R | őõ.AchievesRate R} := by
  use Real.logb 2 (Fintype.card d‚āĀ)
  intro R h
  contrapose h
  exact not_achievesRate_gt_log_dim_in őõ (lt_of_not_ge h)

end AchievesRate

section capacity

/-- Quantum channel capacity is nonnegative. -/
theorem zero_le_quantumCapacity (őõ : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) : 0 ‚Č§ őõ.quantumCapacity :=
  le_csSup (bddAbove_achievesRate őõ) (achievesRate_0 őõ)

/-- Quantum channel capacity is at most log2(D), where D is the input dimension. -/
theorem quantumCapacity_ge_log_dim_in (őõ : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) : őõ.quantumCapacity ‚Č§ Real.logb 2 (Fintype.card d‚āĀ) :=
  Real.sSup_le (by
    intro R h
    contrapose h
    exact not_achievesRate_gt_log_dim_in őõ (lt_of_not_ge h))
  (by
    by_cases h : Nonempty d‚āĀ
    ¬∑ apply Real.logb_nonneg one_lt_two (Nat.one_le_cast.mpr Fintype.card_pos)
    ¬∑ simp [not_nonempty_iff.mp h])

/-- The LSD (Lloyd-Shor-Devetak) theorem: the quantum capacity is at least as large the single-copy coherent
information. The "coherent information" is used in literature to refer to both a function of state and
a channel (`coherentInfo`), or a function of just a channel. In the latter case, the state is implicitly
maximized over. Here we use the former definition and state that the lower bound is true for all states. -/
theorem coherentInfo_le_quantumCapacity (őõ : CPTPMap d‚āĀ d‚āā) (ŌĀ : MState d‚āĀ) : coherentInfo ŌĀ őõ ‚Č§ őõ.quantumCapacity := by
